ialization and biologization of gender have enjoyed a recent upsurge in popularity. Flying in the face of 40 years of gender research, there has been a retreat to the bipolar view of gender. The essays in this volume, primarily based on discourse analysis, seek to expand access to the scientifically based contrary view in order to impede such “oversimplifications of the world”.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aWirtschaftsgeschichte. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aEconomic history.1 aAthenas, Muriel González, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBock von Wülfingen, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGehmacher, Johanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzález Athenas, Muriel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKemper, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehner, Eva Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalich, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNeumann, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaapke, Annika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRuppel, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchenk, Britta-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchnicke, Falko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchnicke, Falko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchober, Sarah-Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is p